# RepoFabric turnkey config — ONE file.
#
# EASIEST: let the guided generator write this file for you (prompts + validates):
#   Linux/UNRAID:  bash deploy/new-repofabric-env.sh
#   Windows:       pwsh deploy/New-RepoFabricEnv.ps1
# OR do it by hand — copy this file and edit the few REQUIRED lines:
#   cp .env.example .env
#
# docker compose auto-loads ./.env (for the stack settings) AND the container
# reads the same file for its secrets. Then:
#   GREENFIELD (this host owns 80/443):  docker compose --profile proxy up -d
#   BEHIND an existing proxy / NPM:      docker compose up -d   (no --profile)
#
# Open https://<your-domain>/setup/ and finish in the browser.

# ============================ REQUIRED ======================================
# 1) Public hostname operators + endpoints use. For the bundled-Caddy HTTPS
#    path it needs a public DNS record pointing here, with inbound TCP 80 + 443
#    reachable (Let's Encrypt validates on 80, serves on 443). Behind your own
#    proxy, that proxy handles TLS and Caddy is not started.
REPOFABRIC_DOMAIN=winget.example.com

# 2) Email for the Let's Encrypt account (cert expiry notices). Only used by the
#    bundled Caddy (--profile proxy).
REPOFABRIC_ACME_EMAIL=admin@example.com

# 3) Session cookie secret. Generate once and paste:
#       openssl rand -hex 32
REPOFABRIC_SESSION_SECRET=

# ============================ MICROSOFT SIGN-IN =============================
# How admins sign in (Microsoft Entra ID / Azure AD). Leave these blank and the
# setup wizard's Identity step will GENERATE a ready-to-run Azure CLI script
# (redirect URI pre-filled) that creates the app registration for you -- paste it
# into Azure Cloud Shell as a tenant admin and copy the three values back. Only
# fill these in if you ALREADY have an app registration.
#   Redirect URI the app must trust:  https://<REPOFABRIC_DOMAIN>/admin/auth/callback
REPOFABRIC_ENTRA_TENANT_ID=
REPOFABRIC_ENTRA_CLIENT_ID=
REPOFABRIC_ENTRA_CLIENT_SECRET=

# ============================ MANIFEST STORE (Gitea) ========================
# The bundled Gitea is provisioned automatically: on first start the
# gitea-provision service creates the publisher admin and mints the access
# token (into a private volume RepoFabric reads). You do NOT create a repo or
# paste a token. Leave this blank. Set it only to point at your OWN Gitea token.
#REPOFABRIC_GITEA_PAT=

# ============================ MULTI-INSTANCE / SIDE-BY-SIDE =================
# One knob namespaces EVERYTHING (container names, the docker network, the
# spawned per-repo Rewinged containers). Leave 'repofabric' for your primary
# stack. To run a SECOND instance on the SAME host (e.g. test a new build beside
# production), clone into a separate folder and, in ITS .env, set this PLUS
# distinct host ports + storage roots + a test subdomain. Walkthrough:
# linux/admin/static/docs/deploy-sidebyside.md
#REPOFABRIC_INSTANCE=repofabric

# Host port bindings — change these for a second instance so the two don't fight
# for ports. (Caddy's 80/443 only bind with --profile proxy.)
#REPOFABRIC_ADMIN_HOST_PORT=8086
#REPOFABRIC_INSTALLERS_HOST_PORT=8091
#REPOFABRIC_REWINGED_HOST_PORT=8090
#REPOFABRIC_GITEA_HOST_PORT=3030
#REPOFABRIC_HTTP_PORT=80
#REPOFABRIC_HTTPS_PORT=443

# ============================ IMAGE SOURCE =================================
# By default the stack uses the published image ringosystems/repofabric:latest.
# Run `docker compose pull` to fetch it, then `docker compose up -d`. Pin a
# version for production (recommended). To build from source instead, run
# `docker compose build` (or `up --build`); the compose build: stanza is kept as
# a fallback.
#REPOFABRIC_IMAGE=ringosystems/repofabric
#REPOFABRIC_IMAGE_TAG=latest

# ============================ STORAGE (UNRAID defaults shown) ===============
# A second instance MUST point these at different folders so the two never share
# state. Defaults match the original UNRAID layout.
#REPOFABRIC_STATE_ROOT=/mnt/cache/appdata/repofabric-linux
#REPOFABRIC_APPDATA_ROOT=/mnt/user/appdata/repofabric
# Keep the container's secrets file somewhere other than this ./.env if you want.
#REPOFABRIC_ENV_FILE=.env

# ============================ OPTIONAL ======================================
#REPOFABRIC_ADMIN_PUBLIC_URL=https://winget.example.com/admin   # default derives from REPOFABRIC_DOMAIN
#REPOFABRIC_INSTALLERS_HOST=installers.example.com              # default installers.<REPOFABRIC_DOMAIN>
#GITEA_PUBLIC_HOST=gitea.example.com
#GITEA_DOMAIN=gitea.example.com
#GITEA_ROOT_URL=https://gitea.example.com/
#REPOFABRIC_DOCKER_GID=281            # UNRAID docker group; lets the container use the docker socket
#REPOFABRIC_COOKIE_SECURE=true
